@Node "What is EClock?" "EClock.guide/What is EClock?"
@Next "Differences Clock-EClock"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"

What is EClock?
***************

EClock is a Clock-prog (what else @{i}:-)@{ui}) which can be started from the
CLI as well as from the Workbench. It's not extraordinary but it
includes some usefull features:  EClock is able to pop up on the
momentary screen automatically, you can choose as many alert times as
you like ...

Why have I renamed Clock v2.2 into EClock?

Clock started as a little assembler program with a source code length of
about 4KB. Because many improvements were sent to me I included most of
them in this source to please your needs @{i}:-)@{ui}. But then suddenly I
reached a point from that on I was searching longer for where to insert
the improvement than coding that feature.  (1) That's why I decided to
completely recode Clock, and change the name.

Because I had to learn Modula II at my university I bought a compiler
for my Amiga. I liked it so much that I decided to write the new EClock
in Modula II, to make it easier to include new features and remove bugs
...

The key-file for registered Clock users is of course the same one as
the one for registered EClock users. That means all registered (See
@{"Registration" Link "Registration"}) Clock Users can use EClock without that requester going
on your nerves, when you start EClock.

---------- Footnotes ----------

(1)  Among programers known as spaghetti code @{i}:-)@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "Differences Clock-EClock" "EClock.guide/Differences Clock-EClock"
@Next "Installation"
@Prev "What is EClock?"
@Toc "Main"

Differences Clock/EClock
************************

   @{b}*@{ub}     There are two modi of EClock:

        -      UsePublicScreens only (See @{"EClockPrefs" Link "Main window gadgets"})      (use only
          PublicScreens to appear on) and therefore is mostly system
          conform.

        -      UseEveryScreen (uses every screen to appear on) is not
          as system conform,      but perhaps you want to have a clock
          that appears also on screens like      DPaint, PPaint ...

   @{b}*@{ub}     EClock now consists of three parts.

        -      EClock, the main program (See @{"EClock" Link "EClock"}), that is active
          the hole time.

        -      EClockPrefs, the configuration program (See @{"EClockPrefs" Link "EClockPrefs"}).

        -      And ERequester (See @{"ERequester" Link "ERequester"}), that is started,
          whenever      you wish an alert requester to appear.

     This division was made, because you don't often have to use the
     configuration program     and therefore don't have to waste the
     memory for this part of EClock.

   @{b}*@{ub}     EClock has no limitation of the number of alert times.
     (See @{"timer-prefs" Link "EClockPrefs timer window"}).      They are depending only of the amount of
     memory you have and from the amount     of processor time you want
     EClock to give for handling the alert times.

   @{b}*@{ub}     EClock supports wildcards. That means you can use e.g.
     @{i}"??:00:00#?"@{ui}   for     an hourly alert or
     @{i}"(??:00:00#?|??:30:00#?)"@{ui}   for an half hourly alert.

   @{b}*@{ub}     EClock is now also able to start an alert at a special date or
     day.      Wirldcards are of course supported so that you can e.g.
     enter     @{i}"(Thu#?|Fr#?)"@{ui} for Thursday and Friday. (Be carefull
     this is localized)

   @{b}*@{ub}     EClock will replace the following 3 characters in the
     requester text:

    @{b}\ @{ub}
          This character will be changed to a return, so that a new
          line is     started in the requester window. Now you are able
          to create nicer     looking requesters with as many lines as
          you like @{i}:-)@{ui}.

    @{b}%t@{ub}
          This character will be replaced by the time the requester is
          started.

    @{b}%d@{ub}
          This character will be replaced by the date the requester is
          started.

   @{b}*@{ub}     Now, you can define as many screens, as you like to open
     EClock on.      (See @{"screen-prefs" Link "EClockPrefs screen window"}).      You can select the x- and
     y-position ... where EClock should open its     window on that
     screen. EClock will always prefer screens, that are placed above
      other ones in the listview gadget.


@EndNode

@Node "Installation" "EClock.guide/Installation"
@Next "Program explanations"
@Prev "Differences Clock-EClock"
@Toc "Main"

Installation
************

At first you have to copy the file ERequester somewhere, where it can
be found by the system (be sure you added it in the path list), but you
should prefer the @{i}"c:"@{ui} directory. You need this file to use the
requester feature of EClock.

Now you should copy the EClock program (and its icon) in the
@{i}"SYS:WBStartup"@{ui} drawer or somewhere else, but then you have to start it
by hand in the @{i}"S:User-Startup"@{ui} sequence. This is the main program of
the EClock package.

Then you should copy EClockPrefs (and its icon) in the @{i}"SYS:Prefs"@{ui}
drawer, because EClock searches for it in that drawer.

If you have installed the locale.library (WB2.1+) and you want to
install the german catalog file (Sorry I have nobody, who translates my
catalog file in other languages than english and german, so if you
would do that and sent it to me you will get the newest registered
version of EClock from me for free!) you have to copy the file
@{i}"EClPrefs.catalog"@{ui} to @{i}"locale:Catalogs/Deutsch"@{ui}.

Now you @{i}have to@{ui} run EClockPrefs and save a configuration, because
EClock needs a proper one to start, otherwise EClock will inform you,
that it couldn't find the prefs file @{i}"env:EClock.config"@{ui} ...

Now you can start EClock and admire it @{i}:-)@{ui}

Or just use the installation script ...


@EndNode

